WCS Parents & Students:

This past week, our staff was hard at work participating in professional development and preparing for the start of school next week. We are excited to welcome back our students in-person on Wednesday, September 9th. While we previously shared details of our reopening plan, there are some important updates and reminders for all parents and students to review before we return next week. This update includes but is not limited to:
- Estimated Bus Pickup Times
- Parent Dropoff & Pickup Times
- Health Screening Reminders
- Mask Requirements
- School Visitor Procedures

Please use the following link to view the full update and we appreciate your help in sharing this information with others in our school community: http://www.willsborocsd.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/District-Update-9-5-20.pdf

post_text:
WCS Parents/Guardians,

Please use the following link to complete a school transportation form for the start of the upcoming school year. The form will ask parents/guardians to identify whether or not they will need school-provided transportation and also the correct pickup and dropoff locations for students. Parent/Guardian selections will lock you into opting in/out of school-provided transportation for the first quarter (10 weeks) of the school year.

*Please submit responses no later than Sunday, August 16th

**For parents/guardians with multiple students, a separate copy of this survey must be completed for each child.

***Please note that students will only be able to have one (1) AM pickup location and one (1) PM pickup location. The AM and PM locations may be different from each other and they do not have to be the student's home address (i.e. daycare or other family member address) but the locations cannot be changed from day to day.

https://forms.gle/5oymMZ95E4nEDjbw5

post_text:
WCS Parents:

P-EBT is a new federal program created to help families during the COVID19 school closures. It provides families $420 in food benefits for EACH child who receives free or reduced-price meals from their school. This new program includes all children who attend Willsboro Central School since the District participates in a free lunch for all program. P-EBT benefits will be issued on new or current EBT cards, which are used like a debit card to purchase food from participating stores. No application is needed. Families will receive benefits between June and early August. More details can be found here: hungersolutionsny.org/pebt

post_text: A reminder that there will be a parade to congratulate our graduates that is open to the public following this evening's commencement ceremony. Full details on the parade can be found below:
shared_text:
Willsboro CSD
June 24 at 2:10 PM ¬∑

WCS Community Members:

Please join us in congratulating the Willsboro Central School Class of 2020 with a parade at the conclusion of their graduation ceremony this Friday, June 26th. With the actual ceremony limited to 150 attendees, we are organizing a parade as an opportunity for other family members and friends to congratulate our Seniors in person. Car lineup will start at 7:15 PM at the Willsboro Fire Station and the parade will begin once the graduation ceremony is over at approximately 7:40 PM. Vehicles in the parade will drive slowly through the school bus loop as graduates are seated along the sidewalk. All participants must remain in their vehicles throughout the parade.

post_text: There is still time to complete your census form online. Within our school district, our response rate is still only approximately 30%. If you haven't already, please consider taking the time to complete your form online.
shared_text:
Willsboro CSD
May 15 at 12:54 PM ¬∑

WCS School Community:

Currently, 52.9% of New Yorkers have completed their 2020 Census from home via the web, phone or mail, which ranks New York 41st in the nation for response rate. In our school district, our response rate is only approximately 25%! We can and must do something to increase this rate. The results of the 2020 Census will determine how billions of federal dollars are allocated including aid to school districts. Ensuring a complete count in our communities is essential to securing crucial federal funding for New York State and for our district. If you haven't replied yet, PLEASE go to: https://2020census.gov/ It takes under 10 minutes to do and will have an impact for years to come. If you can, please also share this post with friends and family.

post_text:
WCS Families:

Today is our last meal delivery for the year. All students will receive a 10-day supply of school meal items for the remaining weekdays through the end of June. As food is being delivered, our drivers will also be collecting any school-owned items that need to be returned. On behalf of our entire school community, thank you to our amazing cafeteria and transportation staff for their hard work in keeping all of our students fed during this difficult time. They have served and delivered thousands of meals to WCS families during the past few months!

Also, please know that while the school meal program is over for the year, the Town of Willsboro will be providing a feeding program during the summer. An informational sign-up sheet for their program will be included in today's school meal delivery.

School Budget Vote & Board Election Results:

The 2020-2021 Willsboro Central School budget passed with roughly a 70% approval rating. Detailed results are as follows:

Proposition 1 (School Budget):
533 YES - 221 NO

Proposition 2 (Board Election):
Krissy Leerkes 482
Emily Phillips 469
Herb Longware 360

Proposition 3 (Bus Purchase):
422 YES - 299 NO

Thank you to everyone who voted in this year's election. Once again, the Willsboro CSD community stepped up for the students to show a strong commitment to providing great educational opportunities for all of our students.

GOVERNOR EXTENDS BUDGET VOTE TO JUNE 16TH

Governor Andrew Cuomo announced in a news release Sunday that he will issue an executive order extending the deadline for school election ballots sent via U.S. mail to Tuesday, June 16. The full text of the order can be found here: https://www.governor.ny.gov/‚Ä¶/no-20239-continuing-temporary‚Ä¶

Therefore, school district residents are able to mail school budget votes to the District if they are received no later than Tuesday, June 16, 2020 by 5:00 pm. This new deadline is also the same date/time that election officials will use to start the process of counting ballots.

Please share this information with friends and family.

post_text:
School Budget Absentee Ballot Confidentiality

Since many voters have not previously used absentee ballots, we have received several inquiries regarding how signed returned absentee ballots will remain confidential and anonymous. School districts are always required to gather signatures on absentee ballots to ensure that they are received from eligible voters. Please see the detailed information sheet below that provides further information on the process that is in place to ensure votes remain confidential.

post_text:
WCS School Community:

Currently, 52.9% of New Yorkers have completed their 2020 Census from home via the web, phone or mail, which ranks New York 41st in the nation for response rate. In our school district, our response rate is only approximately 25%! We can and must do something to increase this rate. The results of the 2020 Census will determine how billions of federal dollars are allocated including aid to school districts. Ensuring a complete count in our communities is essential to securing crucial federal funding for New York State and for our district. If you haven't replied yet, PLEASE go to: https://2020census.gov/ It takes under 10 minutes to do and will have an impact for years to come. If you can, please also share this post with friends and family.

WCS Parents & Students,

Please see a new message from Superintendent Gardner. Message is available in text and pdf here: www.willsborocsd.org/coronavirus

On March 27th Governor Cuomo announced that all public schools in New York State will remain closed until April 15th. This new Executive Order supersedes all previous notifications, including those issued by Willsboro Central School. This order requires us to continue to provide remote instruction and meals to students every weekday through April 14th which includes days during our previously scheduled spring break. As a result, there will be no spring break during the week of April 13-17. Also, a reminder that while we are asking for hard copies of classwork not to be returned for safety reasons, it is important that students complete all assignments as they are given by teachers. Thank you for continuing to partner with us.

post_text: As part of our ongoing mission to keep our students safe, Willsboro CSD has installed stop-arm cameras on all of our school buses. As part of a bill signed into law this summer, Governor Cuomo officially made footage from stop-arm cameras admissible to prosecute anyone illegally passing a school bus while its red loading lights are activated. These newly installed camera units feature high definition video and still frame photos. They are positioned to see the license plate and driver of any passing vehicle. It is our hope that by adding these cameras to our bus fleet we will be better equipped to help prevent unfortunate and avoidable situations. Please feel free to share this posting with friends and family. #WillsboroPride

post_text: WCS music students attended a special event organized by our friends at Moriah Central School. The presentation, The Instrument of Hope, was inspired by an organization called Shine MSD ‚Äî which stands for Marjory Stoneman Douglas, the Parkland, Fla., high school where 17 people were killed in a mass shooting on Feb. 14, 2018. Shine MSD is an organization of Parkland students and their parents whose mission is to promote healing through the arts ‚Äî and through this instrument, which is touring the country.

post_text:
Earlier this week, WCS music teacher, Mrs. Jennifer Moore, was one of five women recognized by the Girl Scouts of Northeastern New York at their annual Women of Distinction event. Mrs. Moore received the 2019 Distinguished Community Leader award for her hard work and dedication to both her students here at WCS and the region as a whole. Congratulations, Mrs. Moore!

Another honoree that night was Mrs. Miriam (Mimi) Lane. Mimi is another recipient from this event with ties to our community. She received the 2019 Innovative Leader Award.

Thank you to both of you for all that you do for our students, our school, and our community! #WillsboroPride

post_text: Don't forget that ALL students eat for free at WCS this year! We are happy to provide healthy, tasty, fresh-made meals for our students each and every day. Meals on Friday always include a homemade dessert. Also, if your child brings a lunch, they can use our "Pick 3 Free" option by taking 3 items being served that day as long as one of them is a fruit or vegetable. #WillsboroPride

post_text: WCS students were excited to start a new science project earlier today. Students in Mrs. Valachovic's 4-6 science classes helped plant greens and veggies that they will grow themselves year-round using new indoor grow carts that were delivered today. These students will grow fresh greens, veggies, and spices that will be served in our cafeteria! The grow cart systems were made possible through the CFES GEAR UP grant and will help students make real-world connections with their science curriculum. We can't wait to taste the fresh food that will be produced! #WillsboroPride
